==English==

===Etymology===
First attested in 1600. From {{etyl|la}} {{term|abstemius|abstēmius|abstaining from wine|lang=la}}; from {{term|ab||lang=la}}, {{term|abs||from|lang=la}} + root of {{term|temetum|tēmētum|[[intoxicating]] drink|lang=la}}, akin to {{etyl|de}} {{term|damlich|dämlich|stupid, silly|lang=de}}, {{etyl|non}} {{term|tham|thām|mugginess|lang=non}}, {{etyl|sga}} {{term|tam|tām|death|lang=sga}}, {{etyl|sa}} {{term|tamyati|tāmyati|he becomes stunned, exhausted|lang=sa}}. {{rfscript|Deva|lang=sa}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æb.ˈsti.mi.əs/}}
* {{rhymes|iːmiəs}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# {{context|obsolete|Late Latin}} [[abstaining|Abstaining]] from wine.
#* Under his special eye '''Abstemious''' I grew up and thrived amain. - [[w:John Milton|John Milton]]
# [[sparing|Sparing]] in diet; [[refraining]] from a free use of food and strong drinks; [[temperate]]; [[abstinent]]; [[sparing]] in the [[indulgence]] of the appetite or passions.
#* Instances of longevity are chiefly among the '''abstemious''' - [[w:John Arbuthnot|John Arbuthnot]].
# [[sparing|Sparingly]] used; used with [[temperance]] or [[moderation]]
#* an '''abstemious''' diet - [[w:Edward Gibbon|Edward Gibbon]]
# Marked by, or [[spent]] in, [[abstinence]]; as, an ''abstemious'' life.
#* One '''abstemious''' day. - [[w:Alexander Pope|Alexander Pope]]
# {{context|rare}} [[promotive|Promotive]] of [[abstemiousness]]
#* Such is the virtue of the '''abstemious''' well. - [[w:John Dryden|John Dryden]]
